justification_reason: The report stated that it was "very unlikely" that terrorists were going to target America and it is a big deal to ground all aircraft travel, so I think the President was justified in deciding not to order all planes to be grounded.
He had the intelligence but chose not to act on it.
Because the probability was only 20%, it is reasonable to not ground all aircraft.
a threat like this  should be considered.
he is commander and chief. he should take responsibilty
The President used his current knowledge to his best ability
People's lives are more important than money, however, financial consequences should be considered.
trying to protect the lives of Americans....his job.
It wasn't his fault
He saved the US a lot of money, which was smart, but had the attack occurred, he would have knowingly put many lives in danger.

The President had information that the attack would take place and that the only way to avoid it was to ground all passenger planes. However, it is his/her executive decision at the end of the day, and given that there wasn't any concrete evidence that would have taken place, the grounding of all passenger planes could have been an economic loss in itself. It really matters how reliable and certain the information was about the impending attack.
He has the responsibility of protecting the American people at all cost although many people need to travel.
The effect of lives lost and fear inflicted on the nation is greater than the economic loss
He was told it was unlikely that an attack would occur
He believed the cost of grounding all passenger aircraft outweighed the cost of the potential bombing
If it were not for his decision, the attack would have resulted in a devastating outcome.
The President was concerned for the well-being of the American public and had to respond to a perceived threat
Even though it's expensive, intelligence predicted a 70% chance of a terrorist attack which is high.
I think the president was somewhat justified because of the lives that were risked. If it had not been a hoax then that risk is unacceptable
Knowing what has happened with regard to terrorist attacks in the past, these steps were necessary to protect the citizens.
He received intelligence reports that led him to believe that there was no threat of a terrorist attack. He made a decision based on the information that was available to him at the time.
To prevent economic loss
There are public threats everyday, which must be evaluated by the President and intelligence agencies. Choosing which to respond to is a case by case matter.
They unnecessarily put a innocent people in danger and in doing so also made us vulnerable to economic problems.
There was reasonable suspicion that people flying on airlines were in considerable danger. It is better to be safe than sorry, and in this instance, it paid off financially and security-wise.
The consequences for not grounding the flights were huge economically and many people died. In addition, this set off a large panic and was devastating to many
Grounding all passengers from all aircraft is extreme and not justifiable.
He evaluated the potential risk vs. the cost
Because there was no legit reason to ground the planes
There was only a 20% chance of the possibility of a terrorist attack, so I believe it was somewhat justified.
advisors approval, saved the lives of others, saved the government billions of dollars
he tried to save lives by grounding aircrafts, but because the threat was only 20% likely, it is highly unlikely it would've occurred. so it was somewhat justified, but the consequences were massive
Unjustified because reports indicating nothing would probably happen anyway, and nothing did happen
should have grounded
There was a potential terrorist attack putting people at risk.
it was required
reasonable

He took the necessary measures to prevent a terrorist attack which could have cost thousands of lives and millions of dollars. However, I didn't choose "Very justififed" or "Completely justified" because his action was too drastic and could have impacted people's lives and more broadly speaking, the entire country in a negative way.

If he didn't ground the planes and something happened, it'd be really bad, but his decision saved the country a lot of money. Maybe it is just luck that he is justified because if the situation had occurred differently, he'd be in a lot of trouble
He was somewhat justified because it did not seem like an imminent threat.
Better safe than sorry - the president would have been held responsible had he not taken action, so he needed to take action in the interest of safety.
The President has the authority to make these decisions, but intelligence indicated that the threat was not serious.
He gambled with peoples lives when he had the opportunity so save them.
The President was not justified at all because there was prior knowledge of a very possible terrorist attack and there was the possibility to avoid it.
I think the President was justified because of the high chance (70%) of the attack, and the costs of having such an attack take place.
He was justified because he saved people's lives and money
he took the chance that it was a hoax, economical reasons
Safety is paramount concern
There was an attack that could have caused damage and hurt people.
By not risking the event and grounding all aircrafts, he not only saved citizens but the economy as well

Based on the credible intelligence reports, it was made apparent that a terrorist attack would be an unlikely scenario. Furthermore, taking immediate and reflexive action on a threat that lacks credence shows a rush to judgement and weakness on the part of our society. That is, the ultimate aims of terrorist regimes succeed when the United States succumbs to fear. A degree of uncertainty will always exist in such situations, but as a nation and a society, it should not hinder daily activity unless there is near certainty of a dangerous outcome.
The President was justified because his actions saved lives and money.

It seems the justification may have also taken into account the amount of money it would have cost to ground all the flights, and did not make his decision with the safety of airline passengers in mind.
The President knew there was a threat and did not do anything to prevent this incident occurring.

The president exercised caution with the knowledge that he had available to him. The information that later surfaced that it was a hoax does not make the threat illegitimate, and the president did what he though was best.
I think it is based on the credibility of the information. If it is very highly likely, then I think he has the right to take his measure to save his citizens
did not ground all airplanes
He had reason to believe the safety of Americans was a risk.
He originally thought the threat was unlikely to occur
Because it was highly likely that lives and welfare would be at stake
He saved the passengers and also saved the country a 100 billion dollars
People could have died, and saving lives outweighs financial costs.
I think the lives of innocent people who contribute to the economy are more important than the economy itself.
There wasn't a guarantee that the attack would have occurred or not (only 70% probability) so he was justified either way.
Potential cost of the terrorist attack outweighs monetary cost of lost dollars.
There was little intelligence information that a terrorist attack would occur.
The domestic safety of the country should be a top priority of the President, so action should have been taken in response to a serious threat
shows he valued lives over money
He was unjustified because it was a very low probability, but at the same time, he is responsible for an entire country and many lives and any report of a threat should be alarming to him.
lives have more value than money
While the situation was a hoax, it is safer to ensure the safety of innocent people's lives than to risk the death of thousands of people.

You cannot cancel all ground flights because of a threat. There are too many threats for the president to take action for every single one of them. Also, this study didn't specify the extent of the legitimacy/ severity of the initial threat so it's hard to judge..
He is justified because even though it probably costed the nation monetary costs to stop the airplanes, it saved lives.

As the President of the United States there is a certain level of automatic trust the American people (which would include me) have in the President. That trust, as well as the sense of duty that comes with that office entitles the President to make decisions they feel are necessary to keep the country running as best as it can, its people as safe as they can. With that in mind, I believe the President to be somewhat justified in almost any thing they do...as a president. As a person, that is another story.
If he had not taken the action, innocent civilians would have been killed.
The threat was 20%. The President didn't know beforehand that an explosion would definitely occur, so the president was justified in not grounding any aircrafts.
Justified- would have been a lot of money. Not justified- can't live in fear.
Grounding all planes may have caused economic costs as well. With limited information, it may have also caused mass panic.
The President is justified in his actions if it regards the people's safety
There was not a serious threat.
he made the best decision he could at the time

I believe the President was somewhat justified because his role is to protect the American people, and due to the risk/threat that was imposed, it is his obligation and under his rights to do what he thinks will protect his people.
There was a possible threat to the country and the President took appropriate action in response to it
Shouldve grounded flights
the life of the people is more important than the money lost, plus that amount is negligible for the US

It is clear that the President wanted to avoid the potential occurrence of an attack, despite the fact that the report indicated that it was unlikely such an attack would occur. It is clear that he was trying to keep Americans safe, which is justified, however because the attack wasn't so likely to occur, he did not need to ground all aircraft.
If the threat had not been a hoax, people would have died and it could have been prevented.
The potential loss of life greatly outweights the monetary cost, and 70% probability is extremely high.
Whether the outcome was positive or negative, I supported his decision and still stand by my support.
He did not trust that flight would be safe so he took the necessary precautions
He was being cautious
unjustified because did not take action against threats
It was a hoax so he didn't have to ground the aircrafts.
Based on the information he had, he made a seemingly good judgement as to whether or not something bad would happen.
I don't think that "intelligence reports" are a valid indicator of terrorist attacks. He took a big risk of losing American lives, but the other option was not completely logical either
He should have told fliers about the potential impending attack if he chose to not ground the flights.

Terrorists threats are made to cause terror in the population and without proof of an actual threat it can be detrimental to alter daily life and would satisfy the hopes of terrorists making such threats.
A 20% risk is large enough that loss to human life outweighs the potential economic loss of grounding all aircraft.
Passengers and airlines understand the risk of flying when there is a threat. Not the president's right to interfere in private business.
The threat was not very valid or able to be proven.
should have taken the threat more seriously

Although the threat was legitimate, a 20% risk is very low and grounding all aircrafts for one day would have only caused the terrorists to change the date of their attack, and it would have inconvenienced millions of people traveling for the holidays. And grounding all the aircrafts would have caused a great amount of terror for the American people, whether or not there was an attack. The terrorists would have done their job.
Justified due to the fact a successful attack would have cost 100 billion to the economy as well as emotional terror/loss of human life
Intelligence reports said it was UNlikely that terrorists would attack the aircraft.
High probability/high risk
his actions did not alter the chance of terrorism

I believe that a 20% chance of death is significant. Anyone is justified in mitigating the chance of their own death, especially if it is significant. However, if we were approaching this completely rationally and objectively, we would measure the expected cost of each situation, and choose the option that minimized the cost.
The negative effects of an attack, had one occurred, outweigh the negative effects of grounding all air traffic for one day.
Because the risk he took paid off. They caught the terrorists and saved money
a threat should not be taken lightly and though it did not occur this time, the money would be worth it if it occurred
I think he was justified.
Saving Lives
He did what was best for the general population
There is always the risk of threat/flight malfunction. The president acted in accordance with his advisers saying that an attack was unlikely, so if anyone is to blame it is the advisers.
He can take action according to how he believes will happen.
The President took into account the consequences and decided it would be better to potentially save many lives and lose money than go ahead as normal and potentially send many people to their deaths.
he has all the facts to make a sound decision
He was concerned about the safety of the people. Since the news of the threat was sudden, it would have been hard to come to a decision, so he could have made a rash decision.
There was an 80% chance that this was a hoax and the President took that risk.

There was danger to the American people and the President is responsible for protecting them. However, Christmas Eve is a very busy flight day so I'm not sure grounding all flights was 100% justified.
One one hand they were justified in their effort to prevent loss of life and monetary loss, but it could also be seen as a sign of weakness by bowing to the threats of terrorists.
There was only a 20% chance of an attack, the cost of grounding planes is also very high
He was justified in taking either action. He has the power to make a decision and he needs to go with the correct one and justify it. Both can be justified.
Because there was only 20% probability of an attack, I think the President's decision could go either way and he/she couldn't be blamed really for either outcome.
The President was unjustified in not grounding all aircraft because they knew there was a risk greater than 50% that there could be a terrorist attack, which would justify landing the aircraft.
It would have harmed innocent people and damaged the economy

If there was no credible information that an attack was highly likely, it isn't realistic or reasonable to expect the President to ground ALL flights. Bush, however, if we are to speak of 9/11, had information that an attack would happen, but chose not to act.
The President was justified because it is better to be safe than sorry when it comes to potential terrorist attacks
Stopping every single plane seems like overkill and unreasonable
